To determine if an integer \( n \) is a power of three, we can use a mathematical approach. Specifically, we can leverage the properties of powers of three. A number \( n \) is a power of three if it can be expressed in the form \( 3^k \) for some integer \( k \).

Here's a Java solution that checks if \( n \) is a power of three without using loops or recursion:

```java
public class PowerOfThree {
    public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        // A power of three must be a positive integer and must end in 1, 3, 9, or 27
        // repeatedly.
        if (n <= 0) {
            return false;
        }
        while (n % 3 == 0) {
            n /= 3;
        }
        return n == 1;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        PowerOfThree powerOfThree = new PowerOfThree();
        System.out.println(powerOfThree.isPowerOfThree(27)); // true
        System.out.println(powerOfThree.isPowerOfThree(0));  // false
        System.out.println(powerOfThree.isPowerOfThree(-1)); // false
    }
}
```

